<ol><li>Every object in the database has a&nbsp;<b>read timestamp</b>&nbsp;and a&nbsp;<b>write timestamp</b>.</li><li>When a transaction starts, it reads the data from a record, causing the&nbsp;<b>read timestamp to be set</b>.</li><li>Before it writes the update back to the record, it&nbsp;<b>checks the read timestamp</b>.</li></ol><div>If this is not the same as the value saved when this transaction started, it will know that another transaction is also taking place on the record.</div>